(51, 149, 48, 'Reseach Innovation Leade', '2024', 'draft', '2024-12-19 22:25:12.775', '2024-12-19 22:25:12.775', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'sent', 'As the Program Leader of the Rice Sector Development Program (Scaling Program) and Principal Scientist in Grain Quality and Post-Harvest Technology at AfricaRice, I have led transformative initiatives across 15 African countries, directly impacting over 1.8 million stakeholders.', '	Stakeholder Empowerment: Spearheaded the establishment of 39 rice multi-stakeholder platforms in 11 countries, aligning research and scaling priorities with farmers, processors, policymakers, and other actors.\n	Policy Alignment: Facilitated the development of key frameworks such as the National Rice Observatory in Cte dIvoire and rice fortification standards, ensuring alignment with national priorities.\n	Capacity Building: Established six Healthy Diet Living Labs across five African countries and trained over 200 scientists and practitioners in scaling climate-smart and nutrition-sensitive innovations.\n	Innovation Scaling: Validated and scaled 20 climate-smart rice innovations, empowering stakeholders to influence priorities and contribute to sustainable transformation.\n', '	Resource Mobilization: Secured over US$79.7 million in funding, including US$22.2 million in bilateral projects under implementation and US$57.5 million in approved proposals.\n	Partnership Development: Facilitated over 100 partnerships with organizations like AfDB, EU, IsDB, and GIZ to scale agrifood innovations and unlock transformative finance.\n	Scaling Impact: Coordinated the REWARD program across 15 West African countries and Madagascar, leveraging over US$32 million in funding to enhance resilient rice value chains.\n	Commercialization: Delivered 55 Healthy Diets innovation packages and developed fortified rice-based products, contributing to improved nutrition and livelihoods.\n', 'Working as AfDBs Rice Compact coordinator and AfDB focal person for AfricaRice, I have within the last 2 years worked with the Bank to develop the Regional Rice Resilient Value Chains Devel-opment Programme in West Africa (REWARD).  The REWARD program covers 15 West Africa countries plus Madagascar. The Climate Smart Agriculture component of the REWARD (CSA-REWARD) has also been developed by tapping from the Climate Action Window which is a com-petitive grant. The following are updates on this program.\n1.	The Technical Regional Component which I lead, worth US$8 million has been approved and disbursement will go effective in Jan 2025.\n2.	The CSA-REWARD Adaptation worth US$ 9.4 million, which I lead has also been approved and the Project Appraisal Report and Negotiations are on-going.\n3.	 The CSA-REWARD Mitigation component worth US$15 million, which I lead has going through the first and critical selection process.\n4.	Led the development of The Gambia REWAD project worth US$39.9 milli', 'I follow instructures and resect procedures and when in doubts I always consult with my supervisor or peers.', '1.	Led the setting up of a consortium of 20 partners composed of seven European Universities (Justus-Liebig University Giessen, Katolieke Universiteit Leuven, Universiteit Gent, Max Planck Gesellschaft, Centro de Investigacin y Tecnologa Agroalimentaria de Aragon, Universittsklinikum Heidelberg, University of Copenhagen), one British University (De Montfort University), three CGIAR Centers (AfricaRice, The Alliance of Bioversity Interna-tional and the International Center for Tropical Agriculture, and International Institute of Tropical Agriculture), three Agri-business vocational training Centers (Agri-business Voca-tional Training Center Dschang, Opportunities Industrialization Center Cote dIvoire, Africa Projects Development Centre Nigeria), one United Nations Agency (World Food Pro-gramme/Centre d\'Excellence Rgional contre la Faim et la Malnutrition), one non-governmental organization (Food Security for Peace and Nutrition Africa), two private companies (Entreprise en Sante et', 'I am highly committed to AfricaRice and its vision and believe that the best days are ahead for the center. The achievements cannot be attributed to me alone but to the dedicated team that I have build since my appointment as head of the grain quality and post-harvest lab and then as Program leader for Rice Sector Development. '),
(52, 5, 149, 'Leader Rsd & Taat Coordinator', '2024', 'draft', '2024-12-20 09:40:34.632', '2024-12-20 09:40:34.632', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'sent', 'In addition to supervising routine laboratory analyses, I was able to:\n- Identify 10 nutrient-rich natural products that we use to produce crackers. \n- Develop the process for these products and carry out nutritional analyzes on the products developed.\n- Develop the protocols for analyzing phytic acid in rice and all other foods and have analyzed over 875 samples this year, although this is a very delicate analysis that takes two days to analyze 10 samples.\n- Develop the protocol for chemical analysis of proteins in rice and all other foods and analyzed over 200 samples this year. \n- and write a manuscript which is being corrected and which will be submitted very soon.', 'I have implemented protocols for the preparation of Hibiscus, Baobab, Tamarind, Ginger, Moringa, Soy Milk and Tiger Nut extracts, to produce crackers and enriched instant flours. These innovative and nutritious products were obtained, and I carried out the nutritional analyzes and shared the results with my supervisor. I have set up the protein analysis protocol by the QuantiPro-BCA method and the analysis of phytic acid by the method (K-PHYT from Megazyme), I am already preparing the TOTAL STARCH analysis method (-AMYLASE / AMYLOGLUCOSIDASE) in rice and other products by the Megazyme K-TSTA-100A method. These protocols are currently used in the laboratory for the analysis of MAFF2023 samples, storage experiment samples, cracker samples, etc. Under the guidance of my supervisor, I was able to write project reports such as PADFA, FADCI and scientific documents such as articles (a manuscript already written).', 'Always punctual, diligent, studious, anticipates and plans my work to achieve my objectives. My commitment to achieving objectives means that I am ready to come to work at M\'B on certain weekends without demanding payment for overtime.', 'Ability to deal with unforeseen events and resolve problems to optimize the achievement of objectives. Ability to anticipate avoiding blockages. For example, to avoid slowdowns in my 2025 analyses, I have already ordered the necessary reagents for 2025. ', 'Very active in the interest of my unit and the Center. Apply and fully respect the instructions and regulations of the Center.', NULL, 'The objectives set for this year have been achieved. Indeed, these objectives were set for 2024 and 2025 and what is expected for 2024 has been achieved. However, our work during this period has not been limited to these objectives. Several other activities were also carried out such as participation in the study in collaboration with the team of the Directorate of School Canteens of Cte-d\'Ivoire on the evaluation of the nutritional quality of dishes as part of the revision of dishes manuals. In this study I participated in the preparation of 93 dishes and the collection of 279 samples. Mineral and protein analyze have already been carried out on samples from 60 dishes. I participated in the CGIAR listening session in Cte d\'Ivoire where I was a notetaker. I participated as rapporteur in the workshop aimed at building a rice disease diagnosis and surveillance network in Africa. I participated in MITA 2024 in Lome, organized by CORAF where I exhibited and presented AfricaRice innovatio'),
