(247, 'ok', '2024', 149, 48, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-18 10:27:41.085', '2024-08-18 10:27:41.085', NULL, 'Lead the Rice Sector Development Program', 'Provide scientific and technical guidance to program staff and ensure that they publish papers\nLead the development of new project such as the REWARD Program (Regional + CAW) and the Science Program of Scaling (SP9).\nSupport countries in the implementation of their rice-self-sufficiency programmes - The Gambia is an example.\nReinforce the seed unit to ensure that it is efficient and effective in responding to seed needs.', 'Available support staff\nBetter working conditions for staff\nThe channel of communication with staff of the program should be following so that the Program Leader can effectively monitor the activities of staffs.', '2024-12-31', 'Three papers published and two under review\n\nTang EN, Ndindeng SA, Onaga G, Ortega-Beltran A, Falade DOT, Djouaka R & Frei M. (2024). Mycotoxin concentrations in rice are affected by chalkiness, grain shape, processing type and grain origin. Mycotoxin Research.\n\nDossou-Yovo ER, Ibrahim Ali, Akpoffo MAY, Belko N, Ndindeng SA, Saito K, Futakuchi K. 2024. Agronomic and economic evaluation of ratoon rice cropping systems with perennial rice varieties in West Africa. Field Crops Research 308, 109294. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.fcr.2024.109294\n\nLevai LD, Tang EN, Monono YE, Ndikum SB, Eyenga EF, Sumbele SA, Ngane Bk, Schneider T, Birmingham T, Ndindeng SA, Ngome FA. 2024. The physicochemical and nutritional properties of biscuits from low temperature dried breadfruit (Artocarpus altilis (Parkinson) Fosberg) flour. Food Measure. https://doi.org/10.1007/s11694-024-02505-x\n\nFive projects submitted and four approved and one pending.\n\nBuilding resilient seed systems for rice, cassava, soybeans, coffee, and fish value chains to strengthen food and economic diversification in Liberia, European Union,  6.5 Million\n\nRegional Rice Resilient Value Chains Development Program (REWARD) AfricaRice-led Regional Project, US$ 8 million\n\nMitigating greenhouse gas emissions in rice value chains in West Africa (mitigation component of AfDB-funded REWARD multi-national program), US$ 9.4 million\n\nThe Gambia accelerated rice production initiative (GARSI) US$ 39 million\n\nLed the S4IP writing team from AfricaRice and was selected by the CGIAR on a competitive basis as one of the co-leads of AoW.\n\n\nTotal quantity of seeds preoduced per seed category :catalyzed the production of 200 tons of foundation seeds in 2024 through TAAT 2 .\n', NULL, '', 'Three papers published.\nTang EN, Ndindeng SA, Onaga G, Ortega-Beltran A, Falade DOT, Djouaka R & Frei M. (2024). Mycotoxinconcentrations in rice are affected by chalkiness, grain shape, processing type and grain origin. Mycotoxin\nResearch (Accepted).\n\nDossou-Yovo ER, Ibrahim Ali, Akpoffo MAY, Belko N, Ndindeng SA, Saito K, Futakuchi K. 2024. Agronomic and economic evaluation of ratoon rice cropping systems with perennial rice varieties in West Africa. Field\nCrops Research 308, 109294. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.fcr.2024.109294\n\nLevai LD, Tang EN, Monono YE, Ndikum SB, Eyenga EF, Sumbele SA, Ngane Bk, Schneider T, Birmingham T,\nNdindeng SA, Ngome FA. 2024. The physicochemical and nutritional properties of biscuits from lowtemperature dried breadfruit (Artocarpus altilis (Parkinson) Fosberg) flour. Food Measure.\nhttps://doi.org/10.1007/s11694-024-02505-x\n\nFour other papers submitted and three accepted for publication in 2025', NULL, NULL),
(248, 'ok', '2024', 196, 244, 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-19 10:32:27.884', '2024-08-19 10:32:27.884', NULL, 'Coordinate and Manage Field Trials', 'Design, coordinte and manage field trials, including; OYT (Observation Yield Trials)AYT (Advanced Yield Trials), and MET (Multi-Environment Trials), under different projects. This includes planning the trials, managing budgets, organizing trial sites, and collecting and analyzing relevant data. Prepare detailed reports with statistical analyses of trial results.', '1-Clear Protocols: Establish standardized protocols for trial design, setup, data collection, and reporting to ensure consistency.\n\n2-Adequate Resources: Allocate sufficient human, financial, and material resources for timely trial execution.\n\n3-Effective Communication: Foster open communication among team members and stakeholders to promptly address challenges and maintain alignment.\n\n4-Robust Data Management: Implement a reliable data management system to ensure accurate data entry, storage, and analysis.\n\n5-Regular Monitoring: Conduct periodic reviews of trial progress, budget adherence, and data quality to identify areas for improvement and take corrective actions.', '2024-12-31', 'Timeliness of Trial Setup: Achieve at least 90% of trials set up on schedule according to planned start dates.\n\nAdherence to Budget: Maintain a budget compliance rate of 95% or higher, ensuring trials are completed within the allocated budget.\n\nAccuracy in Data Collection: Attain a data collection accuracy of 95% by minimizing errors through thorough verification processes.\n\nTimely Reporting: Deliver 90% of reports by their scheduled deadlines to facilitate timely decision-making.\n\nCompleteness of Statistical Analysis: Ensure that 100% of reports include comprehensive statistical analyses of trial results, providing stakeholders with reliable insights.\n\nStakeholder Satisfaction: Achieve an average satisfaction rating of 4 out of 5 from stakeholders regarding the quality of trial management and reporting, assessed through surveys.', 5, 'Excellent fieldmanship.', '', NULL, NULL),
(249, 'ok', '2024', 122, 80, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-19 11:36:46.113', '2024-08-19 11:36:46.113', NULL, 'Objectif 1', 'Etre  mesure de prparer tous les ractifs pour les analyses de laboratoire a 100%\n', 'Mise a ma disposition de tous les protocoles de preparation des reactifs\n', '2024-12-31', 'Savoir preparer les reactif\n', 5, 'Elle s`est vraiment donne les moyens d`atteindre cet objectif car elle reste toujours motiv et dynamique dans l`exercice des taches qui lui sont assigns', 'Bien vrai que l`objectif est atteints pour la preparation des reactifs, nous nous efforcerons de bien garder la cadence et suivre les diffrentes recommandations de notre superviseur.', 'Pour le moment tous les reactifs sont bien prepare au laboratoire', 'Je suis d`accord'),
(250, 'ok', '2024', 122, 80, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-19 11:39:03.810', '2024-08-19 11:39:03.810', NULL, 'Objectif 2', 'Etre capable dexploiter tout appareil ou quipement  du laboratoire a 90% \n', 'Mise a ma disposition des manuels des equipements\n', '2024-12-31', 'Savoir utiliser les equipements du laboratoire\n', 5, 'Kouassi Amoin Nathalie arrive a utiliser tous les quipements du laboratoire sans aucune supervision ce qui nous permet de gagner beaucoup plus de temps.', 'Nous utilisons tous les quipements de laboratoire tout en suivant les procdures de fonctionnement indiques par les fabriquant.\n Avec la supervision de mon superviseur nous pouvons toujours faire encore meilleures.\n', 'Les equipements mis a ma disposition sont bien utiliser dans le laboratoire', 'Nathalie utilise et entretient bien les equipements misent a sa disposition au laboratoire.'),
(251, 'ok', '2024', 122, 80, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-19 11:40:59.839', '2024-08-19 11:40:59.839', NULL, 'Objectif 3', 'Utiliser les quipements de scurit au laboratoire\n', 'Disponibilite des equipements de securite au laboratoire\n', '2024-12-31', 'Utiliser les equipements de securite pendant les manipulations\n', 5, 'Toutes les normes de scurits sont respectes au laboratoire durant les manupulations.', 'Il est indispensable de travailler dans le laboratoire sans des quipements de scurit, nous ferons toujours nos efforts de respecter ce principe et les consignes qui vont avec, Ainsi que les recommandations de notre superviseur.', 'Durant les manupulations nous utilisons toujours les equipements de securite', 'Je suis d`accord avec ces commentaires.'),
(252, 'ok', '2024', 122, 80, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-19 11:43:37.585', '2024-08-19 11:43:37.585', NULL, 'Objectif 4', 'Utiliser et respecter les protocoles danalyse qui seront mis a ma disposition a 90%\n', 'Mise a ma disposition des protocols d`analyse\n', '2024-12-31', 'Savoir conduire les analyses au laboratoire\n', 5, 'Tous les protocoles d`analyses mis a sa disposition sont bien respects pour la conduite des analyses au laboratoire.', 'Le protocole est comme la boussole pour nous sans lui il est difficile de raliser les ractifs dans les normes standards. Alors nous faisons toujours rfrence  lui. pour la conduite des analyses au laboratoire.', 'Pour l`instant toutes les analyses sont bien conduites au laboratoire', 'Nathalie conduit avec succes les analyses qui lui sont confiees au laboratoire.'),
(253, 'ok', '2024', 5, 149, 'draft', 'sent', 'sent', 'sent', '2024-08-20 08:35:53.345', '2024-08-20 08:35:53.345', NULL, 'The anti-nutrients of rice', 'This involves analyzing the concentration of phytic acid in rice samples from the MAFF23 and storage experiment. Phytic acid can form insoluble complexes and is suspected of preventing the absorption of micronutrients contained in the foods we consume by binding to certain minerals including iron, magnesium, zinc and copper. It would be very important to know the phytic acid concentrations of the varieties developed by AfricaRice and its partners, this could show how nutritious the varieties developed really are.', 'Analysis kits and reagents must be available in sufficient quantity. The apparatus to be used must be in good condition at all the times of the analyses.', '2024-12-31', 'Analyze phytic acid concentration for 1600 MAFF samples and 288 samples from storage experiment', NULL, '', 'Analysis kits for around 1000 samples have been acquired and 800 rice samples from MAFF23 experiment and 75 samples of other experiment have already been analyzed. Another batch of analysis kits of around 1000 samples have been ordered for further analysis in 2025.', 'Analysis kits for around 1000 samples have been acquired and 700 rice  samples from MAFF23 experiment and 50 samples of other experiment have already been analyzed. Another batch of analysis kits of around 1000 samples have been ordered for further analysis. ', 'The progress has been excellent and will continue in 2025'),
(254, 'ok', '2024', 5, 149, 'draft', 'sent', 'sent', 'sent', '2024-08-20 11:59:55.465', '2024-08-20 11:59:55.465', NULL, 'Nutrient rich rice crackers formulation', 'A cracker is a thin, crispy snack produced from unleavened dough, considered one of the most popular snacks in the world. Because rice flour does not contain gluten, rice crackers are suitable for people with celiac disease. Rice crackers are believed to contain less fat than wheat crackers, making them good for people prone to obesity and cardiovascular problems. However, the vitamin and mineral content of rice is low, and milling causes additional losses which affect the quality of the resulting rice crackers. Therefore, fortification with natural products found locally such as moringa, baobab, etc. could improve the nutritional quality of rice crackers.  It is in this context that the objective is to produce rice crackers fortified with nutrient rich natural products. ', 'The 10 natural products must be identified and approved first.', '2024-12-31', 'Produce rice crackers using 10 natural products', NULL, '', 'The 10 natural products were identified such as baobab, hibiscus, moringa, tiger nut, ginger, tamarind, soybean, peanut, coconut and cocoa powder. The production of crackers resulted in products that were used in several innovative and nutritious product exhibitions. Analyzes such as proteins, phytic acid, minerals, texture, viscosity of cracker powder and color were carried out on these products. These products were greatly appreciated by the various visitors, which encourages us to move quickly towards the optimization which is planned for 2025.', 'The 10 natural products were identified such as, baobab, hibiscus, moringa, tigernut, ginger, tamarind, soy, peanut, coconut and cocoa. The production of crackers is underway with tests which have resulted in products which have been used in several exhibitions of innovative and nutritious products. 7 extracts and their corresponding products were analyzed. These products were greatly appreciated by the various visitors, which encourages us to evolve quickly.', 'The progress has been excellent. Work will continue in 2025'),
(255, 'ok', '2024', 5, 149, 'draft', 'sent', 'sent', 'sent', '2024-08-20 12:01:55.546', '2024-08-20 12:01:55.546', NULL, 'Optimization of rice crackers production', 'Optimization will allow, using a mathematical model, to understand the effect of the different natural products used on rice crackers quality. We will also be able to highlight the best recipes or the standard recipe for the standardization of the products developed.', 'Objective 1 must be completed first and statistical material for optimization experimets must be available.', '2024-12-31', 'Perform optimization experiments', NULL, '', 'This optimization experiment takes place after the identification of natural products and the implementation of preliminary tests. We completed preliminary testing with the 10 natural products this year and plan to launch production according to the RSM design in 2025.', 'This optimization experiment comes after the identification of natural products and the implementation of preliminary tests. We hope to complete preliminary testing with the 10 natural products and are preparing to launch production according to the RSM design.', 'There is need to fast-track this next year expecally now that the cracker production process has been stabilized'),
(256, 'ok', '2024', 225, 76, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-20 12:13:26.325', '2024-08-20 12:13:26.325', NULL, 'Species complex associated with Brown Spot', 'Support the identification of the species complex associated with Brown Spot by samples isolation , by\nDNA Extraction and Genotyping GBS', 'Successful analysis of genotyping data to identify and classify species or strains, using appropriate bioinformatics tools and methodologies.', '2024-12-31', '-Number of samples isolated collection\n-Species identified', NULL, '', 'Not Completed, continuous work: I have made significant progress in samples isolation and increasing the number of isolates in our collection. Preliminary findings have been documented, and the analysis is ongoing to confirm species-level identifications.', '70 samples have been isolated from samples collected of 05 differents sites in Ivory Coast and sequenced by GBS', ''),
(257, 'ok', '2024', 225, 76, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-20 12:13:40.109', '2024-08-20 12:13:40.109', NULL, 'Update of BS and Rice Blast pathogen diversity', 'Support the head of plant pathology unit in the update of Brown Spot (BS) and Rice Blast pathogen diversity by isolation and storage of samples from differents sources. \n and restyping of 150 rice blast isolates on monogenic lines', '- Successful collection and isolation of samples from diverse sources to ensure comprehensive representation of Brown Spot and Rice Blast pathogens.\n- Effective storage of isolated samples to maintain their viability and integrity for future analysis.\n-High-quality and reliable data generated from the restyping process, including a classification of pathogen strains.', '2024-12-31', '- Number of samples collected from various sources for Brown Spot and Rice Blast pathogens.\n- Percentage of samples from which pathogens are successfully isolated.\n-Number of blast isolates classified', NULL, '', 'Not Completed, continuous work:The work to update pathogen diversity for Brown Spot and Rice Blast is advancing well. I have made the isolation of 70 monospores of brown spots from different places in the Ivory Coast during my stay in France. The GBS analysis is still ongoing.  		', 'the restyping process is ongoing', ''),
(258, 'ok', '2024', 225, 76, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-20 12:16:15.043', '2024-08-20 12:16:15.043', NULL, ' Rice Blast modeling to predict disease risks', 'Support studies on Rice Blast modeling by conducting experiment to predict disease risks and monitoring the disease.', '-Completion of experiments \n-Determine the time when the rate infection is high or not according the weather', '2024-12-31', '- Develop and implement at least two \nexperimental setups to collect reliable data on disease risk factors.\n- Monitor disease development across two locations  to assess risk variability.\n- Conduct disease monitoring at regular intervals weekly during wet and dry seasons.\n', NULL, '', 'Completed :	I have successfully supported experiments for Rice Blast disease modeling, including the setup and monitoring of trials. Data on environmental factors and disease progression have been collected and will be analyzed. 		', 'Data collection is ongoing', ''),
(259, 'ok', '2024', 225, 76, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-20 12:20:01.583', '2024-08-20 12:20:01.583', NULL, 'Response of Glaberrima to Rice Blast under drought', 'Conduct the Screening of 336 Glaberrima lines to rice Blast in greenhouse and the study of the response of Glaberrima to Rice Blast under drought conditions.\n\n', 'High-quality and precise data collection on Glaberrima\'s physiological, and molecular responses to combined Rice Blast and drought stress.', '2024-12-31', '- Number of varieties resistantes to rice blast in screenhouse\n- Varieties resistants to rice blast under drought conditions', NULL, '', 'Completed : Experiments to evaluate Oryza glaberrima responses to Rice Blast under drought conditions have been completed. Observations on disease severity and drought interactions have been recorded. The data is currently being processed for statistical analysis, and the results will contribute to identifying resistant traits in Glaberrima germplasm.', 'Resistants varieties have been identified to Rice blast, drought screening is ongoing', ''),
(261, 'ok', '2024', 5, 149, 'draft', 'sent', 'sent', 'sent', '2024-08-20 13:05:26.674', '2024-08-20 13:05:26.674', NULL, 'Sensory analysis of rice crackers developed', 'After the physicochemical evaluation and acceptability of a new developed product, it is very important to evaluate the sensory profile of this new product to allow reproducibility and standardization. A panel of tasters will be trained and used to characterize the crackers developed to highlight the sensory profile of each product.', 'Optimization experiment must end first', '2024-12-31', 'Perform descriptive and affective profiling test', NULL, '', 'The sensory evaluation will be carried out on the products obtained after the optimization experiment. Everything is being done for the success of this very sensitive experiment. The methodology to be used has already been written.', 'The sensory evaluation will be carried out on the products obtained after the optimization experiment. Everything is being done for the success of this very sensitive experiment. The methodology to be used has already been written.', 'The sensory protocol has been developed and this work will be done in partnership with CITA, Spain'),
(262, 'ok', '2024', 5, 149, 'draft', 'sent', 'sent', 'sent', '2024-08-20 13:12:06.984', '2024-08-20 13:12:06.984', NULL, 'Scientific document writing', 'Prepare manuscripts for scientific valorization of the work carried out', 'For manuscript 2, objectives 2 and 3 must be completed first. \nFor manuscript 3, objective 4 must be completely achieved first.', '2024-12-31', 'Prepare three manuscripts  (1) A review on nutrient dense crops for cracker production and (2) Effect of ingredients on the physicochemical quality and acceptability of rice-based cracker (3) Descriptive and affective profiling of rice-based crackers.', NULL, '', 'The writing of the review manuscript is advanced. A first draft was presented and allowed the team to reframe the objectives of this review manuscript. The different key paragraphs to be developed have been well identified. The second version was finalized and submitted to my supervisor. A detailed document on the production of the crackers, the methodology and all the results obtained was shared with my supervisor.', 'The writing of the review manuscript is advanced. A first draft was presented and allowed the team to reframe the objectives of this review manuscript. The different key paragraphs to be developed have been well identified. The second version of the draft is in progress.', 'Progress has been made but need to be fast-tracked in 2025'),
(263, 'ok', '2024', 225, 76, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-20 15:18:24.711', '2024-08-20 15:18:24.711', NULL, 'Perform data analysis and report writing.', 'Analyze collected data and produce comprehensive reports, applying statistical and analytical methods to interpret data and presenting the results in a clear, structured format', 'The data analysis is rigorous and that the report provides valuable insights', '2024-12-31', 'Data analysis tasks and report sections completed within the planned timeline.', NULL, '', 'On going : Data analysis for the trials and pathogen diversity studies is in progress. Final reports are being prepared and will be completed .', 'Data collection on trials have been collected', ''),
(269, 'ok', '2024', 158, 149, 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-21 12:42:41.088', '2024-08-21 12:42:41.088', NULL, 'Varietal resistance/tolerance to AfRGM', 'Screening 55 Oryza sativa lines (MET) for resistance/tolerance to AfRGM under artificial (paddy screenhouse) and natural infestation (Edozhigi) in Nigeria. Identification of donors from 155 Oryza glaberrima lines screened for resistance/tolerance to AfRGM under natural infestation at Edozhigi, Nigeria', 'Early supply of quality seed from rice breeders. Provision of adequate funds to support planned activities. Favorable climatic conditions', '2024-12-31', 'At least 2  3 Oryza sativa (MET) lines identified as resistant/tolerant to AfRGM. At least 20  30 Oryza glaberrima lines identified as donors for resistance to AfRGM', NULL, '', '-	Of the 55 Oryza sativa lines (MET) screened for resistance/tolerance to AfRGM under natural infestation at Edozhigi, only ART1522-B-11-1 was moderately resistant to the pest at 70 days after transplanting.\n-	Of the 55 MET lowland Oryza sativa lines evaluated for resistance to AfRGM under artificial infestation, only ART1522-B-11-1 showed moderate susceptibility to the pest with a score of 5. The ART1522-B-8-1 and 38 others were susceptible with a score of 7 and the remaining lines were highly susceptible to the pest, scoring 9 at 70 DAT.\n- Of the 155 Oryza glaberrima accessions evaluated for resistance to African rice gall midge under natural infestation at Edozhigi, 104 accessions were highly resistant to the pest with no damage, 28 accessions resistant, and 22 accessions were moderately resistant to the pest at 63 DAT. Only TOG 6359 was moderately susceptible to the pest\n', '	Of the 55 Oryza sativa lines (MET) screened for resistance/tolerance to AfRGM under natural infestation at Edozhigi, only ART1522-B-11-1 was moderately resistant to the pest at 70 days after transplanting. \n	For the 55 MET lowland Oryza sativa lines evaluated for resistance to AfRGM under artificial infestation, Ibadan, scoring for tiller infestation at 45 DAT to be carried out on 21 October, 2024.\n	Of the 155 Oryza glaberrima accessions evaluated for resistance to African rice gall midge (AfRGM) under natural infestation at Edozhigi, 151 accessions were highly resistant with no damage, four accessions (TOG 14095, TOG 6359, TOG 7205, and TOG 9350) showed moderately resistance to the pest at 21 days after transplanting. \n', ''),
(270, 'ok', '2024', 158, 149, 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-21 12:50:15.546', '2024-08-21 12:50:15.546', NULL, 'Plant Health Initiative Activities', 'Execute plant health initiative (PHI) activities on (i) commercial biopesticides for the control of stem borers, (ii) validation of the use of neem & orange lime solutions for control of stem borers, and (iii) optimization of field scouting techniques for rice insect population monitoring and damage thresholds', 'Provision of adequate funds for the activities. Favorable climatic conditions', '2024-12-31', 'At least 1 or 2 commercial biopesticides promoted & scaled to farmers in the farming communities', NULL, '', 'i)	At least two plant-based biopesticides Azadirachta indica (trade name: Raktin) and Eucalyptus sp (trade name: Lyptol) promoted and scaled to farmers because they are effective for control of African rice gall midge and Diopsis sp in the farming communities where AfRGM and stem borers are endemic in Nigeria and Burkina Faso.    \nii)	Supervision of 1 PhD in Nigeria and 1 PhD in Burkina Faso. Both students have graduated successfully in 2024.\niII)	Farmers who utilized RiceAdvice and Land Area Calculator as digital extension advisory tools on their rice fields experienced reduced incidence/severity of AfRGM and rice stem borer infestations compared to those who did not embrace the innovations in Ebonyi State, Nigeria.\niv) Rice seed soaking with foliar spray of orange lime water solution with crushed neem leaves exhibited more effective control of AfRGM and stem borers than seed-soaking treatment alone. This technology has been promoted to increase knowledge for adoption by farmers. ', '	Second year field trials on evaluation of commercial biopesticides showed that neem and Eucalyptus extracts are highly effective against African rice gall midge and Diopsis sp. than entomopathogenic fungi (Metarhizium anisopliae and Beauveria bassiana) at Edozhigi, Niger State.\n	Field trials on rice seed treatment showed that rice varieties subjected to a combination of seed soaking and field spraying with neem-lime extracts exhibited a remarkable increase in grain yield compared to the untreated control.\n\n', ''),
(271, 'ok', '2024', 158, 149, 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-21 12:53:19.820', '2024-08-21 12:53:19.820', NULL, 'Execution of Zero Hunger project in Togo & Nigeria', 'Execute Zero Hunger project activities in Kara and Savanes region of Togo in partnership with MAEDR & ITRA, Togo and IFAD VCDP in Ebonyi State, Nigeria', 'Timely disbursement of project funds from IITA to AfricaRice  Nigeria, ITRA & MAEDR  Togo. Favorable climatic conditions', '2024-12-31', 'Agricultural productivity of farmers enhanced through training of farmers on GAPs and digital extension advisory tools. Capacity development of women on rice-based products diversification strengthened, etc.', NULL, '', '	Productivity increase: Average rice yield increase from 1.8 to 4.1 tons per ha through:\n-	Enhanced dissemination of climate smart rice varieties  FAROs 44, 66, 67.\n-	Good agricultural practices (quality seed, agronomic and water management practices).\n-	Increased use of digital extension advisory tools (RiceAdvice, Land Area Calculator).\n-	Mechanization support:  Six rice thresher cleaners (1.5 tons/hr capacity) fabricated by 30 Ebonyi State youth/artisans in 2023 were distributed to farmers from the six participating Local Govt. Areas of the State. \n 25 extension agents trained in digital extension advisory services (e.g. RiceAdvice, land area calculator, etc.) in Kara & Savanes regions.\n	The EAs in Kara and Savanes regions have initiated farmers training with 3,000 farmers trained in seed production and GAPs to showcase yield advantage. 	\n	Of the 10 women trained on value addition, one of the trainees have trained 52 women in Namon communities, Kara region.', '	Extension Agents in Kara and Savanna regions have initiated farmers training with 3,000 farmers trained in seed production and GAPs to showcase yield advantage over the local variety. \n	Farmer-led demonstration plots (0.5 ha) established for seed production in four sites (Namon, Boufal, Takpamba and Far) in Savannah and Kara regions. This will lead to availability of high-quality seeds of improved varieties in Togo. \n	Two improved rice varieties (ARICA 6, ARICA 11) released by AfricaRice in the region was promoted by ZH project including local varieties (Exbaika) and IR 64.  \n	Four rice varieties (ARICA 6, ARICA 11, Exbaika and IR 64) were established by the EAs under the guidance of ITRA with at least 10 farmersin each field observing the knowledge transfer.\n	Seed certification protocols were developed to strengthens the seed system.\n	25 extension agents trained on digital extension advisory services (e.g. RiceAdvice, land area calculator, etc.).\n ', ''),
(272, 'ok', '2024', 158, 149, 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-21 12:56:43.493', '2024-08-21 12:56:43.493', NULL, 'Source for bilateral project funds', '	Agricultural Transformation in Nigeria Federal States and Togolese Regions towards achieving Zero Hunger funded by IFAD (IITA has requested for No Cost Extension in 2025).\n	AGRIHUB & YEASA (Youth Employment in Agribusiness and Sustainable Agriculture) Project Phase 2 in Nigeria, Benin Republic and Togo for funding by IFAD Rome (2025  2028). Budget to be determined by October 2024.\n	Transforming Agriculture In Rural Areas For Sustainable Youth Agribusiness Engagement. A collaborative project between IITA, AfricaRice and Aletheia University (Ago-Iwoye, Ogun State) for funding by AfDB (2025  2029). Budget : USD 4.0 million\n', 'Hold regular zoom meetings and discussions with IFAD Rome especially the newly created youth & women in agribusiness department. Constant follow-up with AfDB on the tripartite project proposal', '2024-12-31', 'At least 1 or 2 bilateral projects funded/supported', NULL, '', '	Agricultural Transformation in Nigeria Federal States and Togolese Regions towards achieving Zero Hunger funded by IFAD (2021  2024) at USD 603,000. IFAD has approved NCE for the project until 31 January 2026..\n	Contributed to a new project entitled AfricaRice-GIZ Carbon Off-setting Rice Emissions (CORE) Project in Nigeria funded by GIZ, Germany. The AfricaRice team led by Dr Elliot Dossou-Yovo attended the kick-off workshop at GIZ Abuja Office from 10  12 December, 2024.  \n	Drafted a new project entitled Enhancing Productivity and Resilience of Dry Season Rice Farming in Nigeria for funding by the National Agricultural Development Fund (NADF), Abuja at Naira 2,542,000,000 equivalent USD 1,588,750.\n	Facilitated Nigerias contribution to AfricaRice to the tune of USD 557,260. There is a reversal of payment to AfricaRice from the Federal Ministry of Finance back to the Federal Ministry of Agriculture & Food Security (FMAFS).  ', '	IFAD has approved No Cost Extension for Agricultural Transformation in Nigeria Federal States and Togolese Regions towards achieving Zero Hunger till January 2026 (IITA has sent a revised Agreement to AfricaRice DG for approval).\n	Contributed to a new project entitled AfricaRice-GIZ Carbon Off-setting Rice Emissions (CORE) Project in Nigeria funded by GIZ, Germany (contact person: Dr. Andrea RUEDIGER  she coordinates GIZs activities and partnerships in agriculture and rural development in Nigeria, andrea.ruediger@giz.de) \n	Drafted a new project entitled Enhancing Productivity and Resilience of Dry Season Rice Farming in Nigeria for funding by the National Agricultural Development Fund (NADF), Abuja at Naira 2,542,000,000 equivalent USD 1,588,750 (AfricaRice DG has expressed interest to collaborate with the Executive Secretary/CEO of NADF  Mr. Muhammed Abu Ibrahim).\n', ''),
(273, 'ok', '2024', 158, 149, 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-21 12:59:46.130', '2024-08-21 12:59:46.130', NULL, 'Representative at national meetings & publications', '	Represent AfricaRice at major national meetings/workshops/conferences \n	Submit one or two conference papers\n	Submit at least 2 papers in scientific peer-reviewed journals \n\n', 'Timely payment for published scientific peer-reviewed journals', '2024-12-31', 'At least 1 conference paper and 2 scientific papers published in peer-reviewed journals', NULL, '', '	Represented AfricaRice (TAAT Rice Compact) at the Nigeria SAPZ (Special Agro-Industrial Processing Zone) Phase  II Preparation Mission from 22 April to 3 May 2024 and from 14 October to 1 November 2024. \n	The DFCS and Regional Representative represented AfricaRice at the discussion on administrative & financial challenges in AfricaRice-GIZ Carbon Off-setting Rice Emissions (CORE) project implementation using the lessons learnt during the implementation of CORIS project (2021  2022) to be sure that the CORE project can be entrusted to AfricaRice without issues. The virtual meeting was held on 5 October 2024.\n Nwilene F.E., Adeoti A.O., Shaibu A.A. and Mohammed I. 2024. Impact of Paspalum scrobiculatum on African rice gall midge, Orseolia oryzivora (Diptera: Cecidomyiidae) and yield in lowland rice. Biocontrol Science and Technology (under journal review).\n	https://doi.org/10.22271/27889289.2024.v4.i1c.126.\n    http://www.ijnrd.org/papers/IJNRD2401034.pdf\n', '	Represented AfricaRice (TAAT Rice Compact) at the Nigeria SAPZ (Special Agro-Industrial Processing Zone) Phase  II Preparation Mission from 22 April to 3 May, 2024.\n	Represented AfricaRice (TAAT Rice Compact) at the Nigeria SAPZ (Special Agro-Industrial Processing Zone) Phase II Appraisal Mission from 14 October to 1 November, 2024. \n	Nwilene F.E., Adeoti A.O., Shaibu A.A. and Mohammed I. (2024). Impact of Paspalum scrobiculatum on African rice gall midge, Orseolia oryzivora (Diptera: Cecidomyiidae) and yield in lowland rice. Biocontrol Science and Technology (under journal review).\n	Latvi K., Ouattara D., Nwilene F., Onaga G., Gnankine O. and Nacro S. (2024). Evaluation of the effectiveness of four biopesticides (Bacillus thuringiensis, Trichoderma sp., neem oil and Jatropha curcas oil) and a chemical insecticide, deltamethrin, against Lepidopteran rice stem borers in Western Burkina Faso. Archives of Phytopathology and Plant Protection (submitted).\n\n\n\n', ''),
(274, 'ok', '2024', 222, 149, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-26 09:14:46.491', '2024-08-26 09:14:46.491', NULL, 'Food safety analysis of market rice samples', 'Collect on average 1500 rice samples from rural and urban markets in three to five African countries, analyze for grain quality characteristics and mycotoxins, prepare and ship samples to De Montfort University (Leicester, UK) for heavy metal analysis.', '- Representative sampling in each country,\n- Proper sample handling to prevent degradation of samples and contaminants,\n- Ensure use of aseptic techniques to avoid recontamination of samples,\n- Follow standard procedures for sample collection, handling and analysis to ensure consistency and repeatability,\n- Ensure timely analysis,\n- Accurate documentation,\n- Training and competency of all personnel involved in sample collection and analysis,\n- Quality control and data management to track samples and results, ensuring traceability and accountability', '2024-12-26', '- Quantify the number of market rice samples collected in atleast three countries collected according to the protocol\n- Time of total sample collection to completion of analysis,\n- Number or percentage of samples that meet EU regulatory and safety standards,\n- Percentage of samples contaminated,', NULL, '', '- Earlier samples collected, mycotoxins extracted and quantified and the results known in 2024\n- 47% of samples exceed EU limits for total aflatoxins, \n- 72% contaminated with total aflatoxin,\n- 40% showing coocurrence with fumonisin and zearalenone\n- On average 1024 market samples have been collected from 2 out of 3 countries; Cameroon and Liberia between May and December 2024\n- Sampling of collected market rice for heavy metal analysis to start in January,\n- Samples will be sent to Monfort Univesity for heavy metal analysis by March, 2025', 'Samples collection was completed in Cameroon and samples shipped to AfricaRice in September 2024. Samples have been packaged and ready to be expediated to Montfort University. Protocol already discussed with the team in Liberia and sample collection will end by before December 2024. The Liberia samples will be added to those from Cameroon and sent to Montfort University for heavy metal analysis.', ''),
(275, 'ok', '2024', 222, 149, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-26 09:43:31.322', '2024-08-26 09:43:31.322', NULL, 'Upland rice - vegetable intercropping system', 'Assess the compatibility of 10 upland rice  vegetable intercropping to elucidate the nutritional and economic benefits.', '- Labour availability,\n- Water management,\n- Training and education of all personnel involved in farm activities,\n- Continuous research and development,\n- Economic viability to ensure the system is profitable to farmers', '2025-02-05', '- Upland rice yield,\n- Vegetable (okra, watermelon and zucchini) yield\n- Economic benefits,\n- Nutritional benefits,\n- Water use efficiency,\n- Sustainability gains', NULL, '', '- 10 aromatic upland rice varieties successfully intercropped with okra, watermelon and zucchini,\n- Preliminary yields of the 10 upland rice varieties  ranged from 2.5 - 4.9 ton/ha,\n- Yields of vegetables to be analyzed,\n- Economic gains of intercropping systems highly feasible,\n- Water was used to irrigated rice and vegetables. Water use efficiency will be determined,\n- Sustainability gains will be evaluated at the end of the 2nd season', 'Agronomic data collected and compiled for intercropping of ten aromatic upland rice varieties with watermelon, zucchini and okra. Grain quality analysis and processing of paddy to parboiled rice currently ongoing. \nCost of production will be evaluated and economic feasibility of the intercropping practice assessed.', ''),
(276, 'ok', '2024', 222, 149, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-26 10:32:28.942', '2024-08-26 10:32:28.942', NULL, 'Hermetic storage systems and rice seed quality', 'Investigate the effectiveness of hermetic storage systems to maintain rice seed viability, grain quality and mineral composition of milled rice following long term storage durations.', '- Control storage environment,\n- Standardized protocol,\n- Proper hermetic sealing,\n- Regular monitoring,\n- Replication and validation,\n- Comparative analysis with traditional storage system', '2025-06-06', '- Seed germination rate,\n- Seed viability rate,\n- Moisture content,\n- Grain quality,\n- Mineral composition,\n- Insect infestation,\n- Total microbial load,\n- Storage loss', NULL, '', '- Seed germination rate has been determined for all samples for month 1 to 7,\n- Seed vigor parameters have be measured for all samples for month 1 to 7,\n- Moisture content for all samples has been measured for month 1 to 7,\n- Grain quality has been analyzed for all samples for month 1 to 6,\n- Mineral composition has ben analyzed for all samples for month 1 - 5,\n- Total microbial load has been analyzed for all samples for 3 different months,\n- Storage loss (decrease in weight) will be evaluated at the end of storage. ', 'Storage experiment almost 50% gone with no hitches. All samples for 6 months of storage have been analyzed for physicochemical grain quality and mineral composition. Samples for Months 3, 4 and 5 have been analyzed for microbial load. There is effective monitoring of the storage room and storage conditions have been properly maintained.', ''),
(277, 'ok', '2024', 222, 149, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-26 10:41:34.702', '2024-08-26 10:41:34.702', NULL, 'Train actors on food quality and safety techniques', 'Develop and demonstrate food quality and safety techniques and train value chain actors on innovative techniques of food processing, preservation and storage.', '- Comprehensive training programs,\n- Resource availbility,\n- Policy and regulatory support,\n- Continuous support and follow-up,\n- Stakeholder collaboration,\n- Active engagement and participation of all stakeholders,\n- Feedback mechanisms', '2027-02-05', '- Number of value chain actors trained,\n- Percentage of actors satisfied with trainings,\n- Implementation rate or percentage of participants who adopt and implement innovative techniques,\n- Reduction in food safety incidence in trained communities,\n- Food loss and waste reduction,\n- Product quality improvement,\n- Economic impact', NULL, '', '- Contributed to the trraining of 35 rice seed producers in Cameroon in June 2024,\n- Contributed to the training of 39 trainers on GEM parboiling and food procesing in Cameroon in August 2024,\n- Contributed to the training of 15 seed producers from the transition support fund countries in M\'be Cote d\'Ivoire in July 2024,\n- Contributed to the training of 9 project coordinators from Ghana on GEM parboiling and food safety in M\'be in Dec 2024,\n- Contributed to the training of 5 visiting students/scientists on the rice grain quality in the Grain Quality Laboratory in 2024,\n- Following up with Groups of processors who have adopted the GEM parboiling technology in Cameroon and Cote d\'Ivoire,\n- Trainees and users of the food processing and preservation are expessing utmost satisfcation of product quality,\n- Evaluation of social, nutritional and economic impacts are ongoing and will continue in 2025', 'Three trainings: Training of 25 beneficiaries; with 15 participants from 5 TSF countries, training of 15 participants with 9 from the UNIDO/ITEQ rice project from Northern Ghana and Training of 40 trainers in Cameroon (beneficiaries of the TAAT project). The over 80 trainers were trained on: Postharvest management/handling of paddy, GEM parboiling technology, safety storage and prevention of mycotoxin contamination in rice and rice business models.', ''),
(278, 'ok', '2024', 222, 149, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-26 10:58:47.997', '2024-08-26 10:58:47.997', NULL, 'Conferences and peer-reviewed publication', 'Present two conference papers, prepare and submit three to four manuscripts in peer-reviewed journals and publish two articles in peer-reviewed journals. ', '- Research quality, originality and adherance to journal and conference guidelines,\n- Comprehensive literature review, methodological rigor and timely submission,\n- Data collection and analysis,\n- Writing and communication skils,\n- Funding resources,\n- Institutional support,\n- ', '2024-02-05', '- Number of conference papers presented,\n- Number of manuscripts prepared,\n- Number of manuscripts submitted,\n- Number of articles published,\n- Peer reviewed feedbacks,\n', NULL, '', '- One conference paper presented at the Tropentag conference in September 2024,\n- Three manuscripts prepared in 2024,\n- Two manuscrpits submitted in 2024,\n- One manuscript published in 2024,\n- Two papers reviewed for high impact peered reviewed journals', 'Two international conferences: Launch of the TAAT project in Ghana and the FARA Science and Partnership for Agriculture Conference in Kigali. \nOne manuscript: Mycotoxin concentration in rice is affected by grain dimension, chalkiness and origin was submitted to the Mycotoxin Research Journal.\nManuscripti on: Rice milling and parboiling trade-offs for economic and nutritional gains ongoing preparation.\nHave completed atleast 5 peer-reviewed assignments for high quality journals.', ''),
(279, 'ok', '2024', 215, 244, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-27 10:54:49.050', '2024-08-27 10:54:49.050', NULL, '1.	Redefining and Optimizing Lowland breeding', '1.	Redefining and Optimizing AfricaRice Lowland Rainfed Breeding Program: To deliver increased genetic gain.\n	Specify/ Define a global breeding program aligned to market segment(s), with defined TPP, germplasm development and product evaluation and deployment strategies.\n	Implementation of Modern Parental Selection Strategy / Reconstitution of Crossing block.\n	Optimized breeding scheme- to deliver higher genetic gain with cost-effective, increased speed & higher accuracy.\n	Implement Population improvement by increasing frequency of desirable alleles.\n	Achieving increased heritability of all trails (On-station & On-farm) specific to the breeding pipeline(s) with improved crop management practices, frequent contacts & better communication with stake holders.\n	Efforts towards complete integration and optimization of speed breeding, RCGS and Data-driven decisions.\n', NULL, '2024-12-31', 'All TPP fully aligned to market segments.\nCrossing block fully reconstituted.', 5, 'Excellent work in redefining TPPS for the breeding pipelines.', 'TPPs are now well defined and aligned with corresponding market segments. TELS-R new early maturity pipeline was introduced with new crossing block designed for early segment in 2024. Frequency of high velue alleales such as aroma, abiotic stress tolerance is consistantly incresing in our breeding populations. 2024 BTF trials were sucessfully completed by our NARES and data were analyzed and presented in advancement meeting. All adavancement desisions are based on multi environment data combined analysis results.', NULL, NULL),
(280, 'ok', '2024', 215, 244, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-27 10:55:02.599', '2024-08-27 10:55:02.599', NULL, '2.	Product Evaluation', '2.	Product Evaluation (Testing, Trailing and Data-driven decisions) of specific breeding pipelines:\n	Establishing Stage 1, MET, OFT, NPT trails  With defined testing networks and SOPs.\n	Data collection, Data management, Combined analysis & Data-driven decisions with EBS unit of AfricaRice.\n	Sampling and Coordination for grain quality tests, HT genotyping, disease & pests screening.\n', NULL, '2024-12-31', '1. Different yield trials established and all data shared with breeders and EBS by 32 December 2024.', 5, 'Great trialing work and high data quality, however it is important to work with NARES on thier data quality.', '2024 breeding products evaluation through breding task force was implimented in 9 countries with NARES and AfricaRice breeders. All data are already analyzed and available with EBS unit of AfricaRice for uploading.', NULL, NULL),
(281, 'ok', '2024', 215, 244, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-27 11:02:01.446', '2024-08-27 11:02:01.446', NULL, '3.	Varietal release and quality seed production', '3.	Varietal release, quality seed production and linkage with seed scaling & seed systems research.\n	Nucleus & Breeder seed production of all newly released varieties and checks\n', NULL, '2024-12-31', 'Breeder seed produced for most recent varieties.\n', 4, 'Commendable effort in early generation seed production for newly release varieties, this needs to go futher on following up the certified seed production and uptake by farmers.', 'Breeder seeds were produced for FARO 66, FARO 67, FARO 68 most recenlty released varieties. Seeds are available in our store. Also seeds were also mutiplied for widely tested elite lines that are in realse pipelines in different countries for testing with MET in network in 2025.  ', NULL, NULL),
(282, 'ok', '2024', 215, 244, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-27 11:04:16.228', '2024-08-27 11:04:16.228', NULL, '4.	Resource Mobilization and Capacity Building', '	New Bilateral Grant Proposals (At least -ONE in 2024) \n	Capacity Building Events (Short- & Medium-Term Trainings)- ONE per year.\n', NULL, '2024-12-31', 'At least 1 grant proposal submitted\nAt least participate in 1 capacity building event', 4, 'Great contribution for resource mobilization.', 'Contributed to Draft concept note on new transformative breeding products for rainfed lowland systems in Africa.  This was combined with oter products and submitted to BMGF for new project.\nContributed in finalization of concept note on Enhancing Salinity tolerance for the rice producing region in northern Senegal. This was submitted by irrigated lowland breeder.\n\nParticipated in Breeding modernization, quantitative genetics and data analytics workshop in Senegal in 2024.\n\nSupervised 2 M.Sc. and 2 Ph.D students in 2024.', NULL, NULL);
