(283, 'ok', '2024', 215, 244, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-27 11:05:59.701', '2024-08-27 11:05:59.701', NULL, '5.	Research Publications', '5.	Research Publications (TWO per year), Project Reports, Scientific Flyers, Website content and any other work assigned by the supervisor.', NULL, '2024-12-31', 'At least 2 papers published in reputed peer reviewed journals.', 5, 'Great track record on scientific publications.', 'Publications: \n1.	Semwal VK, Kobi KO, Futakuchi K, Venuprasad R (2024). Identification of African rice genotypes with early morning flowering trait to avoid heat stress. Plant Genetic Resources: Characterization and Utilization 22: 417-421. https://doi.org/10.1017/ S1479262124000467. (SCI Impact Factor -1.2).\n2.	Shaibu AA, Semwal VK, Nwilene FE, Adeoti AO, Audu SD (2024) Review of abiotic stress tolerance of African Rice (Oryza glaberrima). International J of Novel Research and Development. 9 (1) e297-e317. (SCI Impact Factor -1.76).\n\nRposrts Etc: contributed to reports of ABI, AGGRI-2 and MHRA projects in 2024. In collaboration with other scientists developed posters for display at AfricaRice station Ibadan on RiceAdvise, Smart Valleys, Climate smart varieties etc innovations.\n\nCompiled brief profiles of all GDI scientists for website development and submitted to program leader.\n\nOrganized monthly GDI program update meeting and developed summaries for key discussion/ action points.', NULL, NULL),
(284, 'ok', '2024', 217, 244, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-28 15:49:32.581', '2024-08-28 15:49:32.581', NULL, 'Centralized Accelerated Germplasm Development ', 'Improve & Optimize Centralized accelrated germplasm development fsacility\n	Maintenace and strengthening of RGA facility.\n	Improve and Optimize RGA protocols for shortening of breeding cycle.\n	Optimize no. of crosses, population size & generation advancements for different breeding programs.\n\n', NULL, '2024-12-31', 'Breeding cycle = < 3 years for all breeding pipelines of AfricaRice\nTotal number of lines developed/pipeline  as  per recomonded no. of crosses, and population size defined for 1 x pipelize size', 5, 'Outstanding contribution for cetralized breeding scheme.', 'A field based RGA system which shortens the breeding cycle from 6- 7 years  to 3 years through SSD approach is fully operational  at the centralized  accelerated germplasm development facility at Mbe. A cycle time of 3 years from crossing to yield testing gives more than 50% reduction in cycle time compared to the past. In 2024, significant progress was made in terms of the number of crosses, the number of lines developed from these crosses (F2F4), and the number of  lines shipped for Line Stage Trials (LST) across various breeding pipelines and market segments. Over 35,000  F4:F5 lines were developed across all the AR breeding pipelines in 2024. The number of parents crosses and population sizes of AfricaRice Breeding Pipelines were maintained as per the recommendation from CGIAR  breeding optimization team (based on simulation studies). To further reduce the breeding cycle (<3 years), we are also  in process of procuring a semi controlled RGA facility at Mbe.', NULL, NULL),
(285, 'ok', '2024', 217, 244, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-08-28 15:49:40.939', '2024-08-28 15:49:40.939', NULL, '	Resource Mobilization and Capacity Building', 'Capacity Building Events (Short- & Medium-Term Trainings)- \nNew publication in 2024', NULL, '2024-12-31', 'Atleast ONE  training per year\nResearch publications atleast 1-2 \nProject reports submitted\n\n', 4, 'Great contribution for capacity building, need to enhance scientific publications.', 'o	Attended  Breeding Analytics and Quantitative Genetics training organized by  AfricaRice and CGIAR- Genetic Innovation- BRS at Sngal.\no	Facilitated six-month training   to Paul Kimwemwe  from INERA , DRC on modernized breeding techniques and operations   through CGIAR CBLP-CapSha visiting scientist programme.\no	Delivered  a talk on rice standard trialing  procedure in a  workshop on Training of Field technicians on breeding operations  organized by the Breeding and Research Services (BRS). \no	Published 2 manuscripts in 2024 (Transgressive segregation and gene action underlying the inheritance of drought tolerance in rice & on Gendered analysis of rice product profiles, in Cte dIvoire). Drafted 3 manuscripts( a. on low emission rice b. estimated genetic gain from ERA trial & c. Upland Breeding in Africa: Perspectives and achievements.\no	Lead the technical report submission of MI 2024 progress from AR and also contributed significantly to ABI final  report submission.', NULL, NULL),
(286, 'ok', '2024', 16, 73, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-30 08:33:24.638', '2024-08-30 08:33:24.638', NULL, 'FertiCombo trials establishment', 'Conduct second-year testing for the 3 FertiCombo trials and perform residual effect testing across 3 fields where two-year testing was completed in Ankilizato Madagascar.', 'timely preparation and execution of all activities for the trials', '2024-12-31', 'Successful completion of the 6 trials for both wet and dry season 2024', NULL, '', 'The wet and dry season trials for 2024 in Ankilizato have been successfully completed.', 'The wet season trial has been successfully completed. Currently, the dry season trial is underway, progressing as planned. This is expected to be completed by the end of November. After that, a detailed data analysis will be undertaken for the four completed seasons', ''),
(287, 'ok', '2024', 16, 73, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-30 11:10:46.534', '2024-08-30 11:10:46.534', NULL, 'GXEXM trial in 3 countries', 'Under Excellence in Agronomy initiative, the strategic project on Agronomy and Product Quality; establish and manage the GXEXM trial on zinc biofortification in Madagascar and ensure the effective execution of the trials in Cote dIvoire and Senegal.', 'timely preparation and execution of all activities for the trials; regular follow up with the team in Cote divoire et Senegal\n', '2024-12-31', 'Successful completion of the trial in all sites', NULL, '', 'The wet and dry season trial in Madagascar has been completed.\nThe second season trials in Senegal and Cte dIvoire are currently ongoing.\nGrain samples from all three sites are yet to be analyzed.', 'The wet season trial has been successfully completed in the 3 countries, although post-harvest processing is still ongoing. Currently, the dry season trial is established, progressing well and expected to be completed by the end of November in Madagascar and Senegal and early January in Cote d\'Ivoire. Grain samples will subsequently be sent to Cte d\'Ivoire for nutrient analysis.', ''),
(288, 'ok', '2024', 16, 73, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-30 12:28:05.050', '2024-08-30 12:28:05.050', NULL, 'Support for DEFIS and FSRP', 'Provide support for DEFIS and FSRP projects in Madagascar on agronomy activities, including the development of activity plans and protocols', '-	Team engagement\n-	regular follow up with the team in the field\n', '2024-12-31', '-	Protocols developed \n-	Planned activities well established\n', NULL, '', 'Activity plans and protocols for DEFIS have been successfully developed and completed.\nFor FSRP, the activities for each site and the corresponding protocols are still being finalized.', 'For agronomy activities under the DEFIS project, protocols are developed, and activities are implemented for the dry season in the three regions: Atsimo Atsinanana, Vatovavy, and Fitovinany. Regular follow-ups with the field team are conducted to ensure the proper implementation of activities.\n\nFor the FSRP project, a meeting with all FOFIFA researchers working on rice will be conducted soon to discuss the planned activities and selected locations in each intervention region.', ''),
(289, 'ok', '2024', 16, 73, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-30 12:29:12.886', '2024-08-30 12:29:12.886', NULL, 'Support for BRECOMA', 'Support BRECOMA projects activities in Madagascar on GAP demonstrations, P-microdose trials, and farmer training.', 'timely preparation and execution of all activities', '2024-12-31', 'successful completion of all activities under the project', NULL, '', 'All necessary support required for the implementation of BRECOMA activities has been successfully provided.', 'The 2nd year of P microdose trials and GAP demonstration plots have been completed, and off-season crops have been established. All required support regarding the BRECOMA project has been provided. The 3rd season of P microdose trials is starting soon and requires preparation.', ''),
(290, 'ok', '2024', 16, 73, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'sent', '2024-08-30 12:30:15.393', '2024-08-30 12:30:15.393', NULL, 'Data collection and analysis', 'Perform data collection and analysis, write reports and manuscripts, and undertake other professional duties as assigned by the supervisor.', '-	Timely analysis and reporting\n-	Accurate data collection\n', '2024-12-31', '-	Submission of reports and manuscripts within deadlines\n- Completion of data collection and analysis', NULL, '', 'I complete assigned tasks promptly, prioritizing them based on urgency and importance.\nI successfully published a paper as the lead author in the Experimental Agriculture Journal.', 'Data analysis and presentation of results, powerpoint preparation, and report writing have been completed as per the supervisor\'s request. The manuscript on the seeder and fertiseeder has been revised and accepted in the Journal of Experimental Agriculture.', ''),
(291, 'ok', '2024', 217, 244, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-02 11:13:56.792', '2024-09-02 11:13:56.792', NULL, 'Varietal Release', 'Varietal release, quality seed production and linkage with seed scaling & seed systems research.\nNucleus & Breeder seed production of all newly released varieties and checks\n', NULL, '2024-12-31', '2-3 varieties released through upland breeding pipeline', 5, 'Excellent effort in early generation seed production and promoting release of new varities.', 'In 2024, Upland breeding programme had released five high-yielding upland rice varietiesCRAM 1, CRAM 2, CRAM 3, CRAM 4, and CRAM 6designed to enhanced  production in rainfed upland systems in Cte d\'Ivoire. These varieties are early maturing, outperform local varieties(IGUAPE)  in yield, exhibit drought tolerance, and possess resistance to blast disease while maintaining good grain quality. Additionally, CRAM 4 and CRAM 6 are aromatic, a highly desirable trait among consumers in Cte d\'Ivoire. Currently some of varieties  is  under seed production by Center for Agronomic Research (CNRA) with support of Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development, Cte d\'Ivoire for out scaling  by  providing quality  seeds  to farmers and replace the old low yielding upland varieties grown in Cte d\'Ivoire.', NULL, NULL),
(292, 'ok', '2024', 25, 76, 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-03 08:56:00.840', '2024-09-03 08:56:00.840', NULL, 'Validating the seed health status of all incoming ', 'Carry out germplasm acquisition and germplasm distribution from seed request to shipment in compliance with the FAO and IPPC procedure.', 'Without any disease interception', '2024-12-30', 'At least 20 000 seed samples successfullly exchanged.', NULL, '', '10818 accessions were distributed for RBCA, among with 5,258 rice seeds and 4,560 leaves to 14 countries.11 accessions were imported from Madagascar and internally from Agronomy Unit. \n35,277 varieties were sent out for Breeding, comprised of 26,278 rice seed samples and 8,999 leaf samples to 13 countries and 2,887 varieties were imported from 8 countries, \n\nFor other programs, I exported 313 rice seed varieties to eleven (11) countries and 11 legume varieties and 212 isolates, including 44 for Blast and 168 for bacteria I imported 1018 rice seeds from nine (9) countries and other seed varieties imported, including 36 sorghum and 38 millets; 138 soil samples and 44 Blast isolates and 12 symptomatic leaves of fungi and bacteria.\nA total of 145039 diagnostic tests for export and 15876 for import materials\nMore than 46000 seed samples distributed all other the world, with no pest and disease interceptions \n\nField inspections and phytosanitation conducted. 5, 015 acces for RBCA and 4 varie', 'I provided in 2024 at GHU phytosanitary services for the Rice Biodiversity Center for Africa (RBCA), successfully dispatching 3,000 rice seed accessions and 4,560 leaf accessionsa total of 7560 accessionsto 10 countries for 20 events, with no pest or disease interceptions. The seeds were treated in accordance with the import permit requirements of each destination. Countries of export included Italy, Nigeria, Philippines, Cote dIvoire, Liberia, Mali, Sierra Leone, India, USA.\n Additionally, I imported 5 rice seed accessions for the same unit from Madagascar . In total, 15120 diagnostic tests were conducted for export materials and 20 tests for import materials to ensure compliance with phytosanitary import requirements for foreign rice seed requests\nSimilarly, I provided phytosanitary services for breeders, exporting 13,139 rice seed samples and 8,999 leaf samplesa total of 22138 samples', ''),
(293, 'ok', '2024', 25, 76, 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-03 09:17:55.313', '2024-09-03 09:17:55.313', NULL, 'Contribute to the disinfection, cleaning and treat', 'Seed treatments by applying biological, physical, and chemical agents and techniques to seeds to protect them for export and import materials', 'Using SOP-Seed treatment to prepare healthy seeds according to the procedure in order to enhance the establishment of healthy crops.', '2024-12-31', 'At least 20 000 healthy seed samples successfully exchanged', NULL, '', 'For export, a total of 10,818 rice accessions from the Genebank, 35,277 breeding line samples from the Breeding Unit, and 313 rice samples from other units were inspected, treated, and distributed through the GHU to recipients across different countries. For import materials, 11 rice accessions for the Genebank, 2,887 breeding material samples, and 1018 rice samples and 53 sorghum and millet seeds and 138 soil samples from other units that were subjected to laboratory tests, post-entry quarantine in screenhouses, growth-out inspections, and health tests to ensure compliance with phytosanitary requirements in Cte d\'Ivoire.\nAll imported and exported materials were systematically fumigated with 57% Aluminum Phosphide at a rate of 3g/m. Additionally, samples showing visible symptoms were cultured and analyzed to determine the cause of infection before being cleared for release\n', 'For export, a total of 10,818 rice accessions from the Genebank, 15,277 breeding line samples from the Breeding Unit, and 313 rice samples from other units were inspected, treated, and distributed through the GHU to recipients across different countries. For import materials, 11 rice accessions for the Genebank, 1444,3 breeding material samples, and 518 rice samples and 33 sorghum and millet seeds and 111 soil samples from other units that were subjected to laboratory tests, post-entry quarantine in screenhouses, growth-out inspections, and health tests to ensure compliance with phytosanitary requirements in Cte d\'Ivoire.\nAll imported and exported materials were systematically fumigated with 57% Aluminum Phosphide at a rate of 3g/m. Additionally, samples showing visible symptoms were cultured and analyzed to determine the cause of infection before being cleared for release\n', ''),
(294, 'ok', '2024', 25, 76, 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-03 09:19:35.566', '2024-09-03 09:19:35.566', NULL, 'Collaborate with the quarantine services of Cote d', '.Visit of inspection\n.Awareness week\n.Post Entry Quarantine ', '-	Monitoring, clearance and documentation of safe germplasm movement .\n', '2024-12-31', 'No breaches of the host country and receiving countries quarantine protocols  and , and at least 25 CPs and 10 IPs established and documented.\n', NULL, '', 'Collaboration with the NPPO MEMINADER and GHU Phytosanitary awareness week organization\nThere was an agreement that marked a significant step in expediting the shipment of seeds to countries importing from AfricaRice. 46 Import Permits and 75 Phytosanitary Certificates were issued, allowing me to deliver seeds to partners without delay\nGHU organized workshop to host the MEMINADER team at M\'b each year for a visit inspection of GHU activities and to enable the NPPO to give an update on phytosanitary regulatory compliance in Cote dIvoire. \nFrom October 1-5 in 2024, GHU hosted the MEMINADER team from Abidjan and MAAIF team from Uganda at M\'b. Focused on Rice Disease Biosecurity Preparedness. 3 priority pests and diseases were Dickeya  zea , Chilo suppressalis and Ditylenchus angustus .\nPost entry, 11 accessions were released to the RBCA, and 2887 varieties were released to the Breeding and 1018 rice seed samples, 53 other seed crops, 138 soils samples, 56 isolates released to other uni', 'There was an agreement that marked a significant step in expediting the shipment of seeds to countries importing from AfricaRice.\nGHU organized workshop to host the MEMINADER team at M\'b each year. In 2024, we presented research and development activities at AfricaRice, including the Germplasm Health Unit, Genebank activities, and seed health testing and diagnostic methodologies. The MEMINADER team presented and discussed topics related to seed health and regulatory compliance, the issuance of phytosanitary certificates, and new developments in international plant regulations, and how they are implemented in Cte d\'Ivoire, as well as import permit processing and collaboration with AfricaRice. A comprehensive update was provided on pest risk assessment and management, along with the biosecurity strategy, preparedness, surveillance, awareness, and communication. The visit also included awareness week events and training on the identification of fungal seed-borne diseases. ', ''),
(295, 'ok', '2024', 25, 76, 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-03 09:48:35.671', '2024-09-03 09:48:35.671', NULL, 'Research on phytosanitary protocols and diagnostic', 'Development of SOPs on different diagnostic methods .', 'Develop the procedures in line with activities that are conducted.', '2024-11-30', 'At least 3 SOPs developped', NULL, '', 'a)	Heat treatment in combination with chemicals protocol for pathogen elimination in rice seed\n2 synthetic  and two biological products were evaluated using seed plating technique. Our findings show that chemicalTeams is still more efficacious, followed by Fluidioxonil. Biological ANT FM 30P, RB-99TM were little effective in eliminating bacteria but not effective against fungi.\nb)	I developed 3 SOPs: SOP 5; SOP 6 and SOP 8 also contributed to the development of the SOP for the MinION protocol. I have conducted a Pest Risk Analysis on Bakanae and Aspergillus flavus. \nc)	Transmission of Pantoea in rice seeds imported into AfricaRice\nI tested three Pantoea isolates obtained from seeds sourced from the Philippines, Madagascar, and Mali will continue with molecular test to fulfill Kock Post.\ne)	Using molecular tools, I detected four genera of bacteria and identified Aspergillus flavus as a new threat. Conventionnaly, i identified 36 fungal species.', 'a)	Transmission of Pantoea in rice seeds imported into AfricaRice\n		Pantoea spp. is an emerging cause of bacterial blight disease in rice and maize, transmitted through seeds. This disease has the potential to spread to rice-growing areas previously free of infection and could evolve over time, posing a threat to regional rice production. I tested three isolates obtained from seeds sourced from the Philippines, Madagascar, and Mali. These isolates were sequenced and identified in 2022 using Illumina sequencing technology. The transmission rates of Pantoea from infected seeds to seedlings were determined through screenhouse grow-outs. The seedlings were grown from seeds that were either artificially or naturally infected with Pantoea. The seed-to-seedling transmission rate was significantly higher than the seed transmission rates reported in previous studies on maize, suggesting that seed transmission could be a major factor in the spread of this pathogen in rice within the region. ', ''),
