(317, 'ok', '2024', 68, 150, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-17 15:09:57.220', '2024-09-17 15:09:57.220', NULL, 'Revive digital presence', 'Revitalize AfricaRice website and strengthen the media and social-media presence ', 'Content generation is ensured in collaboration with scientist \nFinancial and technical resources are available to renew the website back end \nCollaboration with CGIAR Web team is enforced for AfricaRice web to be a prototype of the new global web strategy\n', '2024-12-31', 'Website is up to date with weekly updates and portrays compelling content\nSocial media are updated as per global standard (number/week) \nWeb and social media traffic increases by 10% at least\n', 4, 'It is a great achievement for the AfricaRice website to be selected as the pilot for this project. This initiative aligns perfectly with a longstanding objective weve been eager to pursue. While the content will be further developed in the next phase, the redesign of the sites architecture marks a critical and promising first step. \nIt has taken time to get here, but I am pleased that we have reached this important milestone.\nOn social media, the evolution is constant because of the good content shared.', 'Website was updated weekly with scientific content, media articles, programs stories & blog post. Content is refined and adapted to social media to generate the link and drag audiences towards all digital platforms.\nNet audience growth for the year is over 2,000 \nImpressions: Over 400,000 (number of times our content was displayed to users)\nEngagements: Over 40,000 (number of times users engaged with our content eg likes, comments, shares, etc.).\nWorking with CGIAR C&O colleagues on brand new website. The project is still in the development phase.\n', NULL, NULL),
(318, 'ok', '2024', 68, 150, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-17 15:14:38.295', '2024-09-17 15:14:38.295', NULL, 'Global Communication ', 'Represent and position AfricaRice within the CGIAR Communication & Outreach Community', 'Funding availability to partake to global events\nTime availability to effectively contribute to the numerous global events\n', '2024-12-31', 'Participate in CGIAR Comms leaders platforms/events\nEnforce AfricaRice voice and position in all global events preparation and execution\n', 4, 'The COP is meeting regularly, and Francine has been actively representing AfricaRice in these engagements. I receive regular updates during our weekly calls on key developments and activities at the CGIAR level.\nI encourage Francine to consider taking on a leadership role within the COP, as this would not only increase AfricaRices visibility but also strengthen our influence and lobbying efforts within the CGIAR system.', 'Good representation in Comms working groups through delegation and sharing of tasks among the team (digital, strategy, Knowledge).\nEffective shared services such meltwater for media monitoring, splash for event management, Canva for graphic design, sharepoint for templates repositories.\n', NULL, NULL),
(319, 'ok', '2024', 68, 150, 'sent', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-17 15:23:50.740', '2024-09-17 15:23:50.740', NULL, 'Internal Communication ', 'Reinforce staff engagement through internal communication actions\n', 'Collaborate with HR on staff enhancement actions\nLeadership commitment for activities budget \n', '2024-12-31', 'Produce biannual internal newsletter for information dissemination\nContribute to staff activities & celebrations to enforce the team spirit\n', 3, 'While I appreciate the good level of engagement with scientists, I must express some disappointment that the newsletter has not yet been produced. This was an important commitment, and despite competing priorities, it needs to be taken up and delivered.\nThe newsletter is a critical tool for internal communication and external visibility, and I encourage the Communications Unit to prioritize its release in the coming period.', 'Support was provided to HR for internal events such as the annual staff retreat, town hall, science week, relocation communication, trainings and conferences updates, Communication biweekly updates.', NULL, NULL),
(320, 'ok', '2024', 196, 244, 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-19 10:19:26.865', '2024-09-19 10:19:26.865', NULL, 'Demonstration and Seed Production', 'Plan, organize, and monitor demonstration trials of newly approved rice varieties. Ensure the production of high-quality seeds for newly approved varieties under the Seed Equal program. Collaborate with seed producers to ensure effective production and compliance with required standards. Report on activities conducted under the Seed Equal program, including results from demonstration trials and details on seed production.', '1-High Germination Rates: Achieve a minimum germination rate of 90% for seeds produced under the Seed Equal program, ensuring that the seeds are viable and ready for planting.\n\n2-Positive Yield Outcomes: Demonstration trials should consistently show yields that are at least 20% higher than the regional average for traditional rice varieties, validating the effectiveness of the newly approved varieties.\n\n3-Farmer Engagement and Feedback: Obtain feedback from at least 80% of participating farmers in the demonstration trials, ensuring they understand the benefits of the new varieties and their cultivation practices.\n\n4-Compliance with Quality Standards: Ensure that 95% of the seed production adheres to established national and international quality standards, including purity, moisture content, and disease-free status.\n\n5-Sustainable Collaboration with Seed Producers: Establish and maintain collaborative partnerships with at least five seed producers, facilitating knowledge transfer and ensuring compliance with quality and production standards through regular meetings and evaluations.', '2024-12-31', 'Yield Performance:  Achieve at least a 10-20% increase in yield for the new varieties within the first growing season, with a target yield of 4-6 tons per hectare depending on variety and conditions.\nSeed Quality Assessment Ensure that at least 95% of the seeds produced meet or exceed quality standards, with a minimum germination rate of 85% and purity levels above 90%.\nFarmer Adoption Rate : Achieve at least a 30% adoption rate among farmers within one year of the demonstration trials, with a long-term target of increasing this rate to 50% within two years.\n4. Training Participation and Effectiveness: Train at least 80% of targeted participants, with 70% reporting effective application of learned practices in their farming activities, assessed through follow-up surveys within three months of training.\n5. Reporting Timeliness and Completeness : Ensure 100% of reports are submitted within the designated timeframe (e.g., within one month of trial completion) and include all required data, with comprehensive analysis of results and recommendations for future actions.', 5, 'Great work with partners and protocols.', '', NULL, NULL),
(321, 'ok', '2024', 196, 244, 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-19 10:19:38.072', '2024-09-19 10:19:38.072', NULL, 'Facilitate the Homologation of Candidate Varieties', 'Facilitate the homologation process for candidate lines for the National Performance Trial (NPT 2) in the Menabe region, in collaboration with FOFIFA and SOC. This includes preparing the necessary trials, organizing committee visits, and managing the steps required for the approval and release of the varieties.', '1-Timely Completion of Trial Preparations: All necessary trials must be fully prepared and operational by the predetermined deadlines, ensuring that each trial is equipped with the required resources and infrastructure to commence as planned.\n\n2-Effective Coordination of Committee Visits: All committee visits must be effectively organized and executed as scheduled, with all stakeholders present, facilitating thorough evaluations and timely feedback on the candidate lines.\n\n3- Streamlined Approval Process: The approval process must be conducted efficiently, with all candidate varieties receiving formal approval within the targeted timeline, minimizing delays and ensuring timely access to new varieties.\n\n4-Comprehensive Documentation Submission: All documentation required for the homologation process must be submitted in a complete and organized manner, meeting all specified requirements to avoid any rework or delays in the approval process.\n\n5-High Levels of Stakeholder Engagement and Satisfaction: Engage stakeholders effectively throughout the homologation process, achieving a high level of satisfaction (rated 4 out of 5 or higher) through regular communication, collaboration, and responsiveness to feedback.', '2024-12-31', 'Trial Preparation Efficiency: Achieve 100% readiness for all trials as per the established timeline to ensure seamless execution.\nCommittee Visit Organization: Ensure that at least 95% of committee visits occur as scheduled, promoting timely evaluations and feedback.\nApproval Process Timeliness: Reduce the average time for the approval process by 20% compared to previous homologation cycles to enhance efficiency and expedite variety release.\nDocumentation Completeness: Achieve a 100% completeness rate for all documentation submissions to facilitate smooth approvals and minimize delays.\nStakeholder Engagement Satisfaction: Attain an average satisfaction rating of 4 out of 5 or higher, reflecting strong partnerships and effective information sharing.', 4, 'Great contribution, but reports should be submitted on time and regular update on field trials is crucial.', '', NULL, NULL),
(322, 'ok', '2024', 73, 48, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-19 15:56:34.817', '2024-09-19 15:56:34.817', NULL, 'Facilitating R4D actions of the program scientists', 'As the results of the facilitaion, the fllowing conditions will be materialized: At least 1.8 journal papers per scientist; at least 3 proposals/CNs are developed/submitted by program scientists; the projects/initiatives coordinated by program scientists progress without serious issues. The R4D actions include contributions to the centers risk management.', 'The prgram staff continue to work without unexpected incidences.', '2024-12-31', 'Number of journal articles published per scientist; number of proposals/CNs are developed/submitted by the program; number of the projects/initiatives coordinated by program scientists successfully progressed or completed.', NULL, '', 'Program staff published 3.29 journal papers per scientist in 2024. Of the total journal publications of the center in 2024, 62% were authored/coauthored by the program scientists. Program scientists successfully coordinated their projects and initiatives (budget reduction of the initiatives in the midst of the year was the case of all initiatives). Reviewed and discussed risks in the soil lab with the lab managerhis immediate supervisor is in Madagascar and I did it as a PL.\nExamples of proposals/CNs prepared by program staff in 2024:\n	Cultivating Rice with Refraction to Optimise Productivity (CRROP), Green Innovation Fund, 0.35 M EURO, Senthilkumar (under review)\n	Regional Rice Value Chain Development Program (RRVCP)-Reverse Linkage, IDB, 1.14 M US$, Ali (approved)\n	AICCRA additional funding, World Bank, 1.6 M US$, Elliott (approved)\nIn addition, Elliott submitted seven proposals/CNs, where three have been approved and four are under review.\n\n', NULL, NULL),
(323, 'ok', '2024', 73, 48, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-19 16:04:08.777', '2024-09-19 16:04:08.777', NULL, 'Project management.', 'On-time reporting and follow up actions, if needed, are made for all projects under coordinationJapan Attributed and MAFF Project.', 'No serious physical drawback.', '2024-12-31', 'Donor reports', NULL, '', 'The MAFF project was successfully completed. The amount of a donor donation for Japan Attributedreviewed and decided every yearwas as same as the amount of 2023 (120,000 US$) though the total amount of MOFA contributions to the whole CG and CG centers in 2024 was reduced at 25% from 2023.', NULL, NULL),
(324, 'ok', '2024', 73, 48, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-19 16:05:59.864', '2024-09-19 16:05:59.864', NULL, 'Field activities.', 'Field trials plannedMAFF demonstration trialswill be successfully conducted with collaborating scientists. The project end workshop of the MAFF project is organized.', 'Success ful collaborations with contributors.', '2024-12-31', 'Donor reports; internal records.', NULL, '', 'Demonstration trials were successfully completed with Belko and Aminou. The project end workshop was organized virtually due to budget constraints. Arrangements after the project were discussed, e.g. ADERIZs and millers actions; continuity of germplasm screening for micronutrients by Giessen University, AfricaRices breeding activities by Shilesh Yadav. In Japan Attributed, Vimal and Negussie have successfully conducted their breeding activities planned.', NULL, NULL),
(325, 'ok', '2024', 73, 48, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-19 16:08:34.547', '2024-09-19 16:08:34.547', NULL, 'Publications.', 'A book on African rice (Oryza glaberrima) that I edit is progressed at the stage of an advanced draft; at least two journal papers published.\n', 'Sufficient available tome to concentrate to editing/writing the book.', '2024-12-31', 'A draft book sent to a publisher (Springer); number of journal papers published.', NULL, '', 'Submission of the draft book to Springer was postponed to 2025. But all of my authored/coauthored chapters have been completed.\nThe following three journal papers were published:\n	Dossou-Yovo ER, Ali I, Akpoffo M, Belko N, Ndindeng SA, Saito K, Futakuchi K. 2024. Agronomic and economic evaluation of ratoon rice cropping systems with perennial rice varieties in West Africa. Field Crops Research 308, 109294. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.fcr.2024.109294 \n	Edwards GI, Nelson K, Luu T, Coast O, Futakuchi K, Kok K. 2024. Twenty-five rice research priorities for sustainable rice systems by 2050. Global Sustainability. https://doi.org/10.1017/sus.2024.17 \n	Semwal VK, Ramaiah V, Futakuchi K, Orou K. 2024. Identification of African rice genotypes with early morning flowering trait to avoid heat stress. Plant Genetic Resources 22(6), 417421. https://doi.org/10.1017/S1479262124000467', NULL, NULL),
(326, 'ok', '2024', 73, 48, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2024-09-19 16:11:44.640', '2024-09-19 16:11:44.640', NULL, 'Resource mobilization.', 'Contribute to at least one proposal/CN development. Proposals/CNs just being checked as a PL are excluded. At least two actions linked to resource mobilization are made.\n\n', 'Existence of the relevant opportunities.', '2024-12-31', 'Number of proposals/CNs submitted; number of relevant actions.', NULL, '', 'Actively contributed to the discussion of CSA-REWARD with AfDB. Guided Elliott for the proposal development of REWARD-Mitigation. Discussions with keynote speakers invited to the 2024 SWProfessors Eric Sacks (Illinois University) and Patricio Grassini (University of Nebraska-Lincoln) for funding and collaborationshave been continued after the SW. Erik, I and other external collaborators targeted USAID but we have to change it.', NULL, NULL),
