(938, 'ok', '2024', 60, 73, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2025-03-26 16:09:32.643', '2025-03-26 16:09:32.643', NULL, 'Appropriate cropping systems for perennial rice', 'Determine appropriate cropping systems to improve grain yield, labor productivity, and profitability using perennial rice varieties in irrigated lowlands of West Africa.', 'Successful field experiments ', '2024-12-31', 'A scientific paper describing the effects of cropping systems and perennial rice varieties on grain yield, labour productivity and profitability  ', NULL, '', 'In this study, I evaluated the effects of cropping system and perennial rice variety on grain yield, labour productivity, and profitability in irrigated lowlands in West Africa. Experiments were conducted over two years at two sites: Mbe (Cote dIvoire) and Ndiaye (Senegal). The treatments consisted of three cropping systems [one transplanting and two ratoons per year (riceratoonratoon), one transplanting and all other ratoons (riceratoon continuous), and transplanting twice a year (ricerice)], and six varieties (five perennial rice varieties: PR101, PR107, PR23, PR24, and PR25 and a local check variety. The results showed that the riceratoonratoon system with PR23 and PR25 at Mbe and PR107 at Ndiaye offers alternative options to the conventional ricerice system for increasing labour productivity and profitability. The paper has been published and is available with the link below. \n\nhttps://doi.org/10.1016/j.fcr.2024.109294\n\n', NULL, NULL),
(939, 'ok', '2024', 60, 73, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2025-03-26 16:10:46.172', '2025-03-26 16:10:46.172', NULL, 'Framework for CSA investments prioritization', 'Establish a participatory framework for prioritizing investments in climate-smart agriculture innovations for rice-based systems.', 'Effective stakeholders engagement in the co-design of the framework', '2024-12-31', 'A scientific paper describing the framework development and implementation ', NULL, '', 'In this study, I developed a participatory framework to identify the most suitable CSA innovations for rice-based systems and analyze barriers, incentives, and institutional roles in their adoption. The process involves identifying and assessing CSA innovations based on their impact on yield, income, climate resilience, greenhouse gas reduction, and considering technical, financial, and gender inclusivity aspects. Barriers such as resource constraints, farmers\' knowledge, and market access are analyzed, while incentives like subsidies, loans, and capacity-building are identified. Applied in Mali, the framework identified drought- and submergence-tolerant rice varieties, perennial rice, and crop rotations as the best-bet CSA innovations, as well as the financial and technical challenges affecting their adoption by farmers. A paper has been published and is available with the link below. \nhttps://doi.org/10.1016/j.atech.2023.100392\n \n', NULL, NULL),
(940, 'ok', '2024', 60, 73, 'draft', 'sent', 'draft', 'draft', '2025-03-26 16:13:39.197', '2025-03-26 16:13:39.197', NULL, 'GHG mitigation options with yield increase benefit', 'Identify management strategies that lower greenhouse gas emissions while enhancing rice yield, input use efficiency, and farmer income in rainfed lowlands.', 'Successful field experiments and operational gas chromatography', '2024-12-31', 'A paper presenting the findings of field experiments that assessed the effects of management practices on greenhouse gas emissions, rice yield, and profitability, and identifyed strategies that minimize emissions and enhance both yield and profitability.', NULL, '', 'Continuous flooding and nitrogen fertilizer use contribute to methane (CH4) and nitrous oxide (N2O) emissions in lowland rice systems. I conducted a two-year field experiment in Cte dIvoire to assess the effects of biochar and nitrogen (N) fertilizer on greenhouse gas emissions, rice yield, and nitrogen productivity. Biochar application reduced CH4 emissions by 1321% but increased N2O emissions by 996%. The highest partial productivity of nitrogen (94.01 kg kg) was achieved with 6 t/ha of biochar combined with 60 kg N/ha under no-tillage, which also increased rice yield by 8% and reduced global warming potential by 10% and greenhouse gas emission intensity by 15% compared to the farmers practices. This combination can be recommended for smallholder farmers to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and increase rice yield and partial productivity of nitrogen. A paper has been submitted to Paddy and Water Environment and is under review. ', NULL, NULL),
